Brenda 2025-03-06 08:45 p.m.
We would submit that substitution was improper.

The statute allowing substitution of a defendant with the State of Mayflower does not apply when "[the action] is brought for a violation of a statute of the State of Mayflower under which such action against an individual is otherwise authorized." 5 MSC 1 3209.2(b).

This action was filed under two individual-capacity torts. 5 MSC 1 3101.4 and 3102.1; see also 5 MSC 1 3212.2 (authorizing individual-capacity actions against employees of the State when their conduct violates clearly established statutory or constitutional rights.)

(The State has no power to simply cloak an individual in its sovereign immunity. See Hopkins v. Clemson Agricultural College, 221 U.S. 636 (1911) ("Neither a state nor an individual can confer upon an agent authority to commit a tort so as to excuse the perpetrator; in such a case, the law of agency has no application, and the individual is liable to suit and injunction.") Nor does the statute cited confer that power.)

The proper course of action from here on out is to treat this as a claim against AdoreDagger; and potentially apply the standard for qualified immunity.

PAPERLESS ORDER: Criminal contempt is punishable by fine or imprisonment, or both, at the discretion of the court. 5 M.S.C. 1 2104.1. The contempt statute permits this punishment to curtail misbehavior in the presence of the court or near thereto obstructing the administration of justice, misbehavior by an officer of the court in officials transactions, and disobedience to a lawful command. 1 M.S.C. 1501; accord 5 M.S.C. 1 2104.1. Based on the record herein, and the Court's March 21, 2025, Paperless Order putting the defendant on notice that their failure to appear would render them in default of said order and subject to the penalties contained therein, the Court finds that the defendant's conduct satisfies the elements of criminal contempt beyond a reasonable doubt. Therefore, it is hereby ORDERED that the defendant shall serve 30 minutes in county jail, effective immediately, until the defendant presents themselves to the proceedings herein. Signed by Judge sadoimpacto on 3/25/2025.
